>>176576897
That character is clearly coined from 五毛 by someone in the modern day simply because /wau/ in Mandarin is not a valid syllable.
Mandarin phonetic rules forbid the semi-vowel initials /w/ and /j/ from appearing behind diphthongs containing their vocalic equivalents /u/ and /j/, hence you cannot get syllables like yai, yei, wao (where the o is actually /u/), or wou.

「しめる」は助動詞で、「させる」みたいな意味がある
「する」の文語的な未然形「せ」に付ける事がよくある(「しない」から「し」も未然形の一つだが、
せず」とも言うし)
広辞苑にでも調べた方がいい

それで「急逝せしめん」の「ん」は推量の助動詞「む」の略で、「あらん事を」みたいな文でよく使われる

>寂しさに思い出さえ切なく滲む。
滲む can be both transitive and intransitive. Here this 滲む is used intransitively.
More importantly, one of "Nounに"'s meanings is "due to the Noun/because of the Noun", being used here. Nouns that allow this usage is limited (probably emotional expressions).
e.g. 喜びにとび上がる = to jump with delight
悲しみに何もやる気が出ない = grief takes away all motivation.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>176538241
A basic rule is that は can replace を (as long as readers can recognize that the replaced particle is を).
So in this case は essentially means を with は's own characteristic.
The same is true of が. は replaces が without changing が's original function. In my opinion は vs が argument is meaningless because they live in different spheres.
Other particles are not be completely replaced by but turned into "compound" particles like に -> には but the logic remains the same. には is essentially に but は's nuance is added.

The third one is 疎んじられる(ウトんじられる), so its answer is 過疎(カソ).
